# Locating Multiple Elements in Selenium
1️⃣ What is Locating Multiple Elements?
In Selenium , We use locator strategies to find elements on a webpage.
When we want:
    1. All button
    2. All links
    3. All Input fields
    4. All Items in a list
We use :
    driver.find_elements()

👉 Notice: find_elements (plural). It returns a list of elements.

2️⃣ Difference Between find_element and find_elements
Method & Element

find_element() -> Single element
find_elements() -> Multiple elements

Example:
    elements = driver.find_elements(By.NAME, "username")
    print(len(elements))

3️⃣ 7 Locator Strategies to Find Multiple Elements
Selenium supports 7 ways to locate elements:
    1️⃣ By.NAME
    Finds all elements with matching name attributes
    driver.find_elements(By.NAME, "username")

    Example HTML:
        <input name="username">
        <input name="username">
✔ Both elements will be returned.

    2️⃣ By.XPATH
    Finds elements using XPath pattern.
    driver.find_elements(By.XPATH, "//form[1]")

    ✔ Useful when ID or name not available
    ⚠ Be careful – complex XPath can break easily.

    3️⃣ By.LINK_TEXT
    Finds links with exact text.
    driver.find_elements(By.LINK_TEXT, "Continue")

    Example:
        <a href="continue.html">Continue</a>
    ✔ Text must match exactly.

    4️⃣ By.PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT
    Finds links using partial text.
    driver.find_elements(By.PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT, "Conti")

    ✔ Matches "Continue"
    ✔ Useful when full text is long.

    5️⃣ By.TAG_NAME
    Finds elements by HTML tag.
    driver.find_elements(By.TAG_NAME, "h1")

    Example:
        <h1>Welcome</h1>
        <h1>About</h1>
    
    6️⃣ By.CLASS_NAME
    Finds elements by class attribute.
    driver.find_elements(By.CLASS_NAME, "content")

    Example:
        <p class="content">Text</p>
    
    ✔ Returns all elements with class="content"
    ⚠ If multiple class names exist, use only one class.

    7️⃣ By.CSS_SELECTOR
    Finds elements using CSS selector.
    driver.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "p.content")

    ✔ Very powerful
    ✔ Cleaner than XPath
    ✔ Preferred in modern automation

4️⃣ Important Notes
🔹 Deprecated Methods
    Old methods like:
    find_elements_by_name()
    find_elements_by_xpath()
    ❌ Deprecated in Selenium 4

    ✔ Use new syntax:
        driver.find_elements(By.NAME, "value")

🔹 What Happens If No Element Found?
    find_elements()
    ✔ Returns empty list []
    ❌ Does NOT raise exception

    But find_element()
    ❌ Raises NoSuchElementException

5️⃣ Example Usage
    from selenium import webdriver
    from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By

    driver = webdriver.Chrome()
    driver.get("https://example.com")

    elements = driver.find_elements(By.TAG_NAME, "a")

    for element in elements:
        print(element.text)

    driver.quit()

    ✔ Opens page
    ✔ Finds all links
    ✔ Prints link text

6️⃣ When to Use Multiple Elements?

    -> Use find_elements() when:
        1. Validating number of items
        2. Working with tables
        3. Handling dropdown options
        4. Clicking multiple similar buttons
        5. Extracting list data
    
